\[\sin (\angle A + \angle B) = \sin (180^\circ - (\angle A + \angle B)) = \sin (\angle A - \angle B).\]By the angle addition formula,
\begin{align*}
\sin (\angle A - \angle B) &= \sin \angle A \cos \angle B - \cos \angle A \sin \angle B \\
&= \frac{\sin \angle A - \sin \angle B}{\cos \angle A + \cos \angle B}.
\end{align*}Hence,
\[\cos \angle A + \cos \angle B = \frac{\sin \angle A - \sin \angle B}{\sin (\angle A - \angle B)}.\]By the angle subtraction formula,
\begin{align*}
\cos (\angle A - \angle B) &= \cos \angle A \cos \angle B + \sin \angle A \sin \angle B \\
&= \frac{\cos \angle A + \cos \angle B}{\sin \angle A + \sin \angle B}.
\end{align*}Hence,
\[\sin \angle A + \sin \angle B = \frac{\cos \angle A + \cos \angle B}{\cos (\angle A - \angle B)}.\]Dividing the equations $\cos \angle A + \cos \angle B = \frac{\sin \angle A - \sin \angle B}{\sin (\angle A - \angle B)}$ and $\sin \angle A + \sin \angle B = \frac{\cos \angle A + \cos \angle B}{\cos (\angle A - \angle B)},$ we get
\[\frac{\sin \angle A + \sin \angle B}{\sin \angle A - \sin \angle B} = \frac{\cos \angle A + \cos \angle B}{\cos (\angle A - \angle B)}.\]Let $u = \sin \angle A,$ $v = \sin \angle B,$ $a = \cos \angle A,$ and $b = \cos \angle B.$  Then
\[\frac{u + v}{u - v} = \frac{a + b}{a b - (u v)},\]so
\[a b - (u v) = (a + b)(u - v).\]Expanding, we get
\[a b - u v = a u - a v + b u - b v,\]so
\[a (u - v) = u (b - v).\]Then
\[a = \frac{u (b - v)}{u - v}.\]Similarly,
\[b = \frac{v (a - u)}{v - u}.\]Let $p = a - u$ and $q = b - v.$  Then
\[\frac{u (q - p)}{p} = a\]and
\[\frac{v (p - q)}{q} = b,\]so
\[\frac{u (q - p)}{p} + \frac{v (p - q)}{q} = a + b.\]Then
\[\frac{u q^2 - u p^2 + v p^2 - v q^2}{p q} = a + b.\]Since $\sin \angle A + \sin \angle B = \sin 70^\circ,$ $u + v = \sin 70^\circ,$ so
\[\frac{(u + v)(p^2 - q^2)}{p q} = a + b.\]Then
\[\frac{\sin 70^\circ (p^2 - q^2)}{p q} = \sin 70^\circ.\]Since $\sin 70^\circ \neq 0,$ we can cancel the factors of $\sin 70^\circ,$ to get
\[\frac{p^2 - q^2}{p q} = 1.\]Then $p^2 - q^2 = p q,$ so $p^2 = p q + q^2 = q (p + q),$ which means $q | p^2.$  Since $p < q,$ the only possibility is $p = 1$ and $q = 2,$ so $(p,q) = \boxed{(1,2)}.$

